with a couple of questions

00:00:37.170 --> 00:00:38.700
and then we'll open
it up to all of you

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:41.360
and hopefully our colleagues
will join shortly.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:46.480
This is a very interesting
program, in terms of the mix

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:49.580
of contemporary popular
artists as well

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:53.610
as the earlier Renaissance
and Baroque music.

00:00:53.610 --> 00:00:57.240
Is this something new for you,
to mix up the types of music?

00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:59.340
Or have you been doing
it for a while?

00:00:59.340 --> 00:01:03.050
&gt;&gt; Anne Sofie von Otter: I mix
-- I frequently mix the composers

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:06.800
and the genres in my
concert programs

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:11.640
because I enjoy it very
much myself, and then I hope

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:13.620
that the audience does too.

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:15.240
And there are plenty
of other singers

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:21.430
who put together different
types of more specialized --

00:01:21.430 --> 00:01:25.470
I mean only Schubert or
only the German Romantics.

00:01:25.470 --> 00:01:29.680
So this is also always been my --

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:31.990
it's always given me a
lot of pleasure to mix,

00:01:31.990 --> 00:01:38.040
to vary the programs
and [inaudible] only

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:42.000
in English Renaissance music I
wouldn't even want to do that.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.010
So this is my little cook-up.

00:01:47.010 --> 00:01:49.580
And because the musicians
are so fabulous,

00:01:49.580 --> 00:01:53.660
they can play these
other types as well.

00:01:53.660 --> 00:01:55.270
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Wonderful.

00:01:55.270 --> 00:02:00.160
Can you tell us how you three
came to start working together?

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:01.740
&gt;&gt; Anne Sofie von Otter:
Oh, there they are.

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:04.510
[ Applause ]

