00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:37.300
&gt;&gt; Anne Sofie von Otter: Well,
Elvis is a really fantastic guy.

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:41.100
He's got so much experience.

00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:48.340 position:56%
He's really, really clever and is a
very creative person, as you know --

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:49.910
anyone who knows Elvis Costello.

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:54.170
I mean he does all kinds of
things and plays and sings

00:06:54.170 --> 00:06:55.760
with all different kinds of people.

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:58.030
And he's just written
a fantastic book.

00:06:58.030 --> 00:07:02.230
So it was a great pleasure
to work with him.

00:07:02.230 --> 00:07:07.100
We had got to know each other
several years before we recorded,

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:11.000
so I really felt that this
was someone I could trust.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:12.990 position:56%
And he'd been to many, many concerts

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:16.370
at different classical
music that I'd sung.

00:07:16.370 --> 00:07:19.730
And we started discussing what
kind of pop music I liked and why.

00:07:19.730 --> 00:07:22.930
And why I didn't like other kinds.

00:07:22.930 --> 00:07:24.370
So it was sent in cassettes.

00:07:24.370 --> 00:07:27.390
This was the day of the cassettes,
so it sent back and forth.

00:07:27.390 --> 00:07:31.950
So all in all it was a
very wonderful experience

00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:38.950 position:56%
and he really knew what he was
doing, doing this you know he had --

00:07:38.950 --> 00:07:41.890
the putting my voice
in the right context

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:46.030
and choosing the good songs
for the disc together.

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:49.810
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Yes.

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:52.730
My microphone runner
disappeared but [inaudible] --

