00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:10.690
And so I wondered is it because
your lute is so well built

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:14.220
that it keeps its tuning?

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:19.490
Or do you play a little -- you know
you change where your finger is

00:11:19.490 --> 00:11:23.400
so then -- because you can hear
I need to play a little higher.

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:25.110
How come?

00:11:25.110 --> 00:11:26.410
&gt;&gt; Thomas Dunford Duration:
It's technology.

00:11:26.410 --> 00:11:31.950
No. It's just because 300
years ago we used gut strings.

00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:35.760
And they were very good at making
gut strings, especially for lutes.

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:38.850
And they were specific and
really great and kept the tuning.

00:11:38.850 --> 00:11:42.590
But it was an art, so
like Stradivarius' process

00:11:42.590 --> 00:11:44.410
for making wood with violin.

00:11:44.410 --> 00:11:48.660
It was very -- a real art
that's been a bit lost.

00:11:48.660 --> 00:11:51.360
And I'm not very satisfied with
the sound of gut strings now

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:54.960
because it's all made
in factories and stuff

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:58.560
so it doesn't sound as,
on the lute, as nice.

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:02.390
So I just used synthetic strings,
which most lute players use

00:12:02.390 --> 00:12:06.380
because if you'd go on
tour San Francisco to --

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:09.950
from LA to Washington and every
day go in different places.

00:12:09.950 --> 00:12:13.410
And you guys would spend your
life listening to tuning.

00:12:13.410 --> 00:12:14.710
It'd be really boring.

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:17.490
&gt;&gt; Anne Sofie von Otter: So
it's because of the strings.

00:12:17.490 --> 00:12:19.050
