&gt;&gt; Thomas Dunford Duration: No.

00:13:54.510 --> 00:13:58.710
[ Laughter ]

00:13:58.710 --> 00:14:00.820 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: A question
following up on that for Anne Sofie.

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:05.120
How have you noticed your voice
evolve throughout your career

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:07.800
and have you done anything
specific to kind of --

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:10.910
&gt;&gt; Anne Sofie von Otter: Well, I
work very hard now that I'm older.

00:14:10.910 --> 00:14:16.450
I've always been quite disciplined
but never as disciplined as now.

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:20.880
I can tell you, if I wouldn't
practice and keep my voice --

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:24.320
work very hard with it -- I
would have to retire immediately

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:27.380
because at my age the
voice really wants to be

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:28.680
like the rest of the
body [inaudible].

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:34.850
So you have to hold it up,
up, up, up, up [laughter].

00:14:34.850 --> 00:14:36.150
It's true.

00:14:36.150 --> 00:14:37.450
I'm not fibbing.

00:14:37.450 --> 00:14:43.360
This is very -- I mean if I just
let it go, it goes wow, wow, wow.

00:14:43.360 --> 00:14:49.330
So to be able to sing Baroque
music and straight tones

00:14:49.330 --> 00:14:54.610
and [inaudible] it's
just very hard work.

00:14:54.610 --> 00:15:00.710
You have to be very -- you have
to think about what you're doing.

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:04.010
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: How does your
warm-up differ from a program

00:15:04.010 --> 00:15:05.940
like this versus the
Mahler that you performed

00:15:05.940 --> 00:15:08.450
at the Kennedy Center
a few weeks ago?

00:15:08.450 --> 00:15:09.750
Or is it the same?

00:15:09.750 --> 00:15:11.610
&gt;&gt; Anne Sofie von Otter: Well,
for Mahler Third Symphony,

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:16.550
which I did a week ago with
a wonderful orchestra here

00:15:16.550 --> 00:15:18.040
and Christoph Eschenbach.

00:15:18.040 --> 00:15:21.090
It was a huge experience.

00:15:21.090 --> 00:15:24.240
It was very intense and I loved it.

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:30.830
But to prepare for that the
instrument is bigger, so to speak,

00:15:30.830 --> 00:15:40.230
and I need to warm up in a bigger
way because I sing differently.

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:43.220
So I still need to warm up.

00:15:43.220 --> 00:15:46.120
Of course, for this but
then when I go out on stage,

00:15:46.120 --> 00:15:49.900 position:56%
I sing in a much more contained way.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:53.870
The warming up itself
is not so different.

