00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:46.100
It's not just [inaudible]
somebody called the red one,

00:18:46.100 --> 00:18:49.350
and my son's trying
to do the same thing.

00:18:49.350 --> 00:18:56.900
So this is now a kind of -- I
guess we all learn from each other.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:19:01.500
But no, unfortunately the
music education, I think,

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:05.140
in most countries but maybe
not in France or in Germany

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:07.570
but in most other countries --

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:08.870
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Cohen: Yeah.

00:19:08.870 --> 00:19:11.960
Well, in England, there's a big
campaign at the moment to try

00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:15.860
to get music much more in
schools for kids and for everyone

00:19:15.860 --> 00:19:17.420
when they're young to do it.

00:19:17.420 --> 00:19:21.850
And I think it's so important
because if you have familiarity

00:19:21.850 --> 00:19:26.670
with that in your youth,
then that's a real pleasure

00:19:26.670 --> 00:19:27.970
to be able to do that your life.

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:30.910
Whether you do it professionally
or not and maybe the audience

00:19:30.910 --> 00:19:32.690
of the future, you
know it's important.

00:19:32.690 --> 00:19:35.300
You know, it's important, I think,
so important that kids [inaudible]

00:19:35.300 --> 00:19:38.450
to music even if they don't want
to do anything after a while.

00:19:38.450 --> 00:19:41.750
That they should be given
the chance, so important.

00:19:41.750 --> 00:19:43.050
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: In France?

00:19:43.050 --> 00:19:44.350
&gt;&gt; Thomas Dunford Duration: Yeah.

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:45.650
It was good.

00:19:45.650 --> 00:19:53.290
But the thing is when you learn
in a conservatory or anything,

00:19:53.290 --> 00:19:56.500
